# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: immudb
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] Don't forget to ⭐ this repo if you like immudb!
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] immudb is a database with built-in cryptographic proof and verification.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] It tracks changes in sensitive data and the integrity of the history will be protected by the clients, without the need to trust the database.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] It can operate as a key-value store, as a document model database, and/or as relational database (SQL).
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] Traditional database transactions and logs are mutable, and therefore there is no way to know for sure if your data has been compromised. immudb is immutable.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] You can add new versions of existing records, but never change or delete records.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] This lets you store critical data without fear of it being tampered.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] Data stored in immudb is cryptographically coherent and verifiable.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] Unlike blockchains, immudb can handle millions of transactions per second, and can be used both as a lightweight service or embedded in your application as a library. immudb runs everywhere, on an IoT device, your notebook, a server, on-premise or in the cloud.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] When used as a relational data database, it supports both transactions and blobs, so there are no limits to the use cases.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] Developers and organizations use immudb to secure and tamper-evident log data, sensor data, sensitive data, transactions, software build recipes, rule-base data, artifacts and even video streams.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] Examples of organizations using immudb today.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] You may download the immudb binary from the latest releases on Github.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] Once you have downloaded immudb, rename it to `immudb`, make sure to mark it as executable, then run it.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] If you are running the Docker image without host networking, make sure to expose ports 3322 and 9497.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] Immudb helm chart creates a persistent volume for storing immudb database.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] Those database are now by default placed in a subdirectory.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] That's for compatibility with ext4 volumes that have a `/lost+found` directory that can confuse immudb.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] Some volume providers, like EBS or DigitalOcean, are using this kind of volumes.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] If we placed database directory on the root of the volume, that `/lost+found` would be treated as a database.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] So we now create a subpath (usually `immudb`) subpath for storing that.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] This is different from what we did on older (<=1.3.1) helm charts, so if you have already some volumes with data you can set value volumeSubPath to false (i.e.: `--set volumeSubPath.enabled=false`) when upgrading so that the old way is used.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] You can alternatively migrate the data in a `/immudb` directory.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] As said before, you can totally disable the use of subPath by setting `volumeSubPath.enabled=false`.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] You can also tune the subfolder path using `volumeSubPath.path` value, if you prefer your data on a different directory than the default `immudb`.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] immudb can store its data in the Amazon S3 service (or a compatible alternative).
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] When working with the external storage, you can enable the option for the remote storage to be the primary source of identifier.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] This way, if immudb is run using ephemeral disks, such as with AWS ECS Fargate, the identifier can be taken from S3.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] You can also use the role-based credentials for more flexible and secure configuration.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] This allows the service to be used with instance role configuration without a user entity.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] Remember, the `IMMUDB_S3_ROLE_ENABLED` parameter still should be on.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] You may download the immuclient binary from the latest releases on Github.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] Once you have downloaded immuclient, rename it to `immuclient`, make sure to mark it as executable, then run it.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] Or just use Docker to run immuclient in a ready-to-use container.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] immudb now supports immutable, structured audit logging of all server operations.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] When enabled, every gRPC operation is recorded as a JSON audit event stored in immudb's own tamper-proof KV store under the `audit:` key prefix.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] Audit events are written asynchronously to avoid impacting request latency.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] They can be queried using the standard `Scan` API with prefix `audit:` and verified with `VerifiableGet` for tamper-proof compliance evidence.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] Events are stored as JSON, ready for export to external SIEM systems (Splunk, ELK, etc.).
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] The `_diff_action` column indicates whether each row was an `INSERT`, `UPDATE`, or `DELETE` within the specified transaction range.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] Both `SINCE`/`AFTER` and `UNTIL`/`BEFORE` period specifiers are supported.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] Standard `WHERE` clauses can be applied to filter results.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] immudb's PostgreSQL wire protocol server now supports a comprehensive set of SQL features for ORM and tool compatibility.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] Connect with any PostgreSQL client (`psql`, pgAdmin, JDBC, SQLAlchemy, Django, GORM, ActiveRecord) and use standard SQL.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] Supported window functions: `ROW_NUMBER`, `RANK`, `DENSE_RANK`, `LAG`, `LEAD`, `FIRST_VALUE`, `LAST_VALUE`, `NTILE`, and window aggregates (`COUNT`, `SUM`, `MIN`, `MAX`, `AVG`).
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] This branch significantly hardens the PostgreSQL wire protocol and SQL engine against the corner cases that real-world ORMs and applications hit.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] Verified workloads now include **Gitea 1.25.5** (full signup → repo creation → git push → issue lifecycle), **Ruby on Rails 7 / ActiveRecord** (Maybe Finance dashboard), **Django**, **GORM**, **XORM**, **golang-migrate**, **SQLAlchemy**, **lib/pq** and **pgx** drivers.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] To get started with development, there is a quickstart in our documentation: or pick a basic running sample from immudb-client-examples.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] Our immudb Playground provides a guided environment to learn the Python SDK.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] We've developed a "language-agnostic SDK" which exposes a REST API for easy consumption by any application. immugw may be a convenient tool when SDKs are not available for the programming language you're using, for experimentation, or just because you prefer your app only uses REST endpoints.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] immudb can handle millions of writes per second.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] You can generate your own benchmarks using the `stress_tool` under `embedded/tools`.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] Open a pull request to add it to the list.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] Learn how to build immudb components in both binary and Docker image form.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] To report bugs or get help, use GitHub's issues.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] immudb is licensed under the Business Source License 1.1.
[src:immudb/blob-readme-md] immudb re-distributes other open-source tools and libraries - Acknowledgements.
[src:immudb/database-p01] In computing, a **database** is an organized collection of data or a type of data store based on the use of a **database management system** (**DBMS**), the software that interacts with end users, applications, and the database itself to capture and analyze the data.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The DBMS additionally encompasses the core facilities provided to administer the database.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The sum total of the database, the DBMS and the associated applications can be referred to as a **database system**.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Often the term "database" is also used loosely to refer to any of the DBMS, the database system or an application associated with the database.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Professional book indexers used index cards in the creation of book indexes until they were replaced by indexing software in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Small databases can be stored on a file system, while large databases are hosted on computer clusters or cloud storage.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The design of databases spans formal techniques and practical considerations, including data modeling, efficient data representation and storage, query languages, security and privacy of sensitive data, and distributed computing issues, including supporting concurrent access and fault tolerance.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Computer scientists may classify database management systems according to the database models that they support.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Relational databases became dominant in the 1980s.
[src:immudb/database-p01] These model data as rows and columns in a series of tables, and the vast majority use SQL for writing and querying data.
[src:immudb/database-p01] In the 2000s, non-relational databases became popular, collectively referred to as NoSQL, because they use different query languages.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The DBMS provides various functions that allow entry, storage and retrieval of large quantities of information and provides ways to manage how that information is organized.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Because of the close relationship between them, the term "database" is often used casually to refer to both a database and the DBMS used to manipulate it.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Outside the world of professional information technology, the term *database* is often used to refer to any collection of related data (such as a spreadsheet or a card index) as size and usage requirements typically necessitate use of a database management system.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Both a database and its DBMS conform to the principles of a particular database model.
[src:immudb/database-p01] "Database system" refers collectively to the database model, database management system, and database.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Physically, database servers are dedicated computers that hold the actual databases and run only the DBMS and related software.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Database servers are usually multiprocessor computers, with generous memory and RAID disk arrays used for stable storage.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Hardware database accelerators, connected to one or more servers via a high-speed channel, are also used in large-volume transaction processing environments.
[src:immudb/database-p01] DBMSs are found at the heart of most database applications.
[src:immudb/database-p01] DBMSs may be built around a custom multitasking kernel with built-in networking support, but modern DBMSs typically rely on a standard operating system to provide these functions.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Since DBMSs comprise a significant market, computer and storage vendors often take into account DBMS requirements in their own development plans.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The sizes, capabilities, and performance of databases and their respective DBMSs have grown in orders of magnitude.
[src:immudb/database-p01] These performance increases were enabled by the technology progress in the areas of processors, computer memory, computer storage, and computer networks.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The concept of a database was made possible by the emergence of direct access storage media such as magnetic disks, which became widely available in the mid-1960s; earlier systems relied on sequential storage of data on magnetic tape.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The subsequent development of database technology can be divided into three eras based on data model or structure: navigational, SQL/relational, and post-relational.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The two main early navigational data models were the hierarchical model and the CODASYL model (network model).
[src:immudb/database-p01] These were characterized by the use of pointers (often physical disk addresses) to follow relationships from one record to another.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The relational model, first proposed in 1970 by Edgar F.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Codd, departed from this tradition by insisting that applications should search for data by content, rather than by following links.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The relational model employs sets of ledger-style tables, each used for a different type of entity.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Only in the mid-1980s did computing hardware become powerful enough to allow the wide deployment of relational systems (DBMSs plus applications).
[src:immudb/database-p01] By the early 1990s, however, relational systems dominated in all large-scale data processing applications, and as of 2018 they remain dominant: IBM Db2, Oracle, MySQL, and Microsoft SQL Server are the most searched DBMS.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The dominant database language, standardized SQL for the relational model, has influenced database languages for other data models.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Object databases were developed in the 1980s to overcome the inconvenience of object–relational impedance mismatch, which led to the coining of the term "post-relational" and also the development of hybrid object–relational databases.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The next generation of post-relational databases in the late 2000s became known as NoSQL databases, introducing fast key–value stores and document-oriented databases.
[src:immudb/database-p01] A competing "next generation" known as NewSQL databases attempted new implementations that retained the relational/SQL model while aiming to match the high performance of NoSQL compared to commercially available relational DBMSs.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The introduction of the term *database* coincided with the availability of direct-access storage (disks and drums) from the mid-1960s onwards.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The term represented a contrast with the tape-based systems of the past, allowing shared interactive use rather than daily batch processing.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The Oxford English Dictionary cites a 1962 report by the System Development Corporation of California as the first to use the term "data-base" in a specific technical sense.
[src:immudb/database-p01] As computers grew in speed and capability, a number of general-purpose database systems emerged; by the mid-1960s a number of such systems had come into commercial use.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Interest in a standard began to grow, and Charles Bachman, author of one such product, the Integrated Data Store (IDS), founded the Database Task Group within CODASYL, the group responsible for the creation and standardization of COBOL.
[src:immudb/database-p01] In 1971, the Database Task Group delivered their standard, which generally became known as the *CODASYL approach*, and soon a number of commercial products based on this approach entered the market.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The CODASYL approach offered applications the ability to navigate around a linked data set which was formed into a large network.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Later systems added B-trees to provide alternate access paths.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Many CODASYL databases also added a declarative query language for end users (as distinct from the navigational API).
[src:immudb/database-p01] However, CODASYL databases were complex and required significant training and effort to produce useful applications.
[src:immudb/database-p01] IBM also had its own DBMS in 1966, known as Information Management System (IMS).
[src:immudb/database-p01] IMS was a development of software written for the Apollo program on the System/360.
[src:immudb/database-p01] IMS was generally similar in concept to CODASYL, but used a strict hierarchy for its model of data navigation instead of CODASYL's network model.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Both concepts later became known as navigational databases due to the way data was accessed: the term was popularized by Bachman's 1973 Turing Award presentation *The Programmer as Navigator*.
[src:immudb/database-p01] IMS is classified by IBM as a hierarchical database.
[src:immudb/database-p01] IDMS and Cincom Systems' TOTAL databases are classified as network databases.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Codd worked at IBM in San Jose, California, in an office primarily involved in the development of hard disk systems.
[src:immudb/database-p01] He was unhappy with the navigational model of the CODASYL approach, notably the lack of a "search" facility.
[src:immudb/database-p01] In 1970, he wrote a number of papers that outlined a new approach to database construction that eventually culminated in the groundbreaking *A Relational Model of Data for Large Shared Data Banks*.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The paper described a new system for storing and working with large databases.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Instead of records being stored in some sort of linked list of free-form records as in CODASYL, Codd's idea was to organize the data as a number of "tables", each table being used for a different type of entity.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Each table would contain a fixed number of columns containing the attributes of the entity.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Splitting the data into a set of normalized tables (or *relations*) aimed to ensure that each "fact" was only stored once, thus simplifying update operations.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Virtual tables called *views* could present the data in different ways for different users, but views could not be directly updated.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Codd used mathematical terms to define the model: relations, tuples, and domains rather than tables, rows, and columns.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The terminology that is now familiar came from early implementations.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Codd would later criticize the tendency for practical implementations to depart from the mathematical foundations on which the model was based.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The use of primary keys (user-oriented identifiers) to represent cross-table relationships, rather than disk addresses, had two primary motivations.
[src:immudb/database-p01] From an engineering perspective, it enabled tables to be relocated and resized without expensive database reorganization.
[src:immudb/database-p01] There is no loss of expressiveness compared with the hierarchic or network models, though the connections between tables are no longer so explicit.
[src:immudb/database-p01] In the hierarchic and network models, records were allowed to have a complex internal structure.
[src:immudb/database-p01] For example, the salary history of an employee might be represented as a "repeating group" within the employee record.
[src:immudb/database-p01] In the relational model, the process of normalization led to such internal structures being replaced by data held in multiple tables, connected only by logical keys.
[src:immudb/database-p01] For instance, a common use of a database system is to track information about users, their name, login information, various addresses and phone numbers.
[src:immudb/database-p01] In the navigational approach, all of this data would be placed in a single variable-length record.
[src:immudb/database-p01] In the relational approach, the data would be *normalized* into a user table, an address table and a phone number table (for instance).
[src:immudb/database-p01] Records would be created in these optional tables only if the address or phone numbers were actually provided.
[src:immudb/database-p01] As well as identifying rows/records using logical identifiers rather than disk addresses, Codd changed the way in which applications assembled data from multiple records.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Rather than requiring applications to gather data one record at a time by navigating the links, they would use a declarative query language that expressed what data was required, rather than the access path by which it should be found.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Finding an efficient access path to the data became the responsibility of the database management system, rather than the application programmer.
[src:immudb/database-p01] This process, called query optimization, depended on the fact that queries were expressed in terms of mathematical logic.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Beginning in 1973, INGRES delivered its first test products which were generally ready for widespread use in 1979.
[src:immudb/database-p01] INGRES was similar to System R in a number of ways, including the use of a "language" for data access, known as QUEL.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Over time, INGRES moved to the emerging SQL standard.
[src:immudb/database-p01] IBM itself did one test implementation of the relational model, PRTV, and a production one, Business System 12, both now discontinued.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Honeywell wrote MRDS for Multics, and now there are two new implementations: Alphora Dataphor and Rel.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Most other DBMS implementations usually called *relational* are actually SQL DBMSs.
[src:immudb/database-p01] In 1970, the University of Michigan began development of the MICRO Information Management System based on D.L.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The university in 1974 hosted a debate between Codd and Bachman which Bruce Lindsay of IBM later described as "throwing lightning bolts at each other!".
[src:immudb/database-p01] MICRO was used to manage very large data sets by the US Department of Labor, the U.S.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Environmental Protection Agency, and researchers from the University of Alberta, the University of Michigan, and Wayne State University.
[src:immudb/database-p01] It ran on IBM mainframe computers using the Michigan Terminal System.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The system remained in production until 1998.
[src:immudb/database-p01] In the 1970s and 1980s, attempts were made to build database systems with integrated hardware and software.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The underlying philosophy was that such integration would provide higher performance at a lower cost.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Examples were IBM System/38, the early offering of Teradata, and the Britton Lee, Inc. database machine.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Another approach to hardware support for database management was ICL's CAFS accelerator, a hardware disk controller with programmable search capabilities.
[src:immudb/database-p01] In the long term, these efforts were generally unsuccessful because specialized database machines could not keep pace with the rapid development and progress of general-purpose computers.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Thus most database systems nowadays are software systems running on general-purpose hardware, using general-purpose computer data storage.
[src:immudb/database-p01] However, this idea is still pursued in certain applications by some companies like Netezza and Oracle (Exadata).
[src:immudb/database-p01] IBM formed a team led by Codd that started working on a prototype system, *System R* despite opposition from others at the company.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The first version was ready in 1974/5, and work then started on multi-table systems in which the data could be split so that all of the data for a record (some of which is optional) did not have to be stored in a single large "chunk".
[src:immudb/database-p01] Subsequent multi-user versions were tested by customers in 1978 and 1979, by which time a standardized query language – SQL – had been added.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Codd's ideas were establishing themselves as both workable and superior to CODASYL, pushing IBM to develop a true production version of System R, known as *SQL/DS*, and, later, *Database 2* (IBM Db2).
[src:immudb/database-p01] Larry Ellison's Oracle Database (or more simply, Oracle) started from a different chain, based on IBM's papers on System R.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Though Oracle V1 implementations were completed in 1978, it was not until Oracle Version 2 when Ellison beat IBM to market in 1979.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Stonebraker went on to apply the lessons from INGRES to develop a new database, Postgres, which is now known as PostgreSQL.
[src:immudb/database-p01] PostgreSQL is often used for global mission-critical applications (the .org and .info domain name registries use it as their primary data store, as do many large companies and financial institutions).
[src:immudb/database-p01] In Sweden, Codd's paper was also read and Mimer SQL was developed in the mid-1970s at Uppsala University.
[src:immudb/database-p01] In 1984, this project was consolidated into an independent enterprise.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Another data model, the entity–relationship model, emerged in 1976 and gained popularity for database design as it emphasized a more familiar description than the earlier relational model.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Later on, entity–relationship constructs were retrofitted as a data modeling construct for the relational model, and the difference between the two has become irrelevant.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Besides IBM and various software companies such as Sybase and Informix Corporation, most large computer hardware vendors by the 1980s had their own database systems such as DEC's VAX Rdb/VMS.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The decade ushered in the age of desktop computing.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The new computers empowered their users with spreadsheets like Lotus 1-2-3 and database software like dBASE.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The dBASE product was lightweight and easy for any computer user to understand out of the box.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Wayne Ratliff, the creator of dBASE, stated: "dBASE was different from programs like BASIC, C, FORTRAN, and COBOL in that a lot of the dirty work had already been done.
[src:immudb/database-p01] By the start of the decade databases had become a billion-dollar industry in about ten years.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The 1990s, along with a rise in object-oriented programming, saw a growth in how data in various databases were handled.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Programmers and designers began to treat the data in their databases as objects.
[src:immudb/database-p01] That is to say that if a person's data were in a database, that person's attributes, such as their address, phone number, and age, were now considered to belong to that person instead of being extraneous data.
[src:immudb/database-p01] This allows for relations between data to be related to objects and their attributes and not to individual fields.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The term "object–relational impedance mismatch" described the inconvenience of translating between programmed objects and database tables.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Object databases and object–relational databases attempt to solve this problem by providing an object-oriented language (sometimes as extensions to SQL) that programmers can use as alternative to purely relational SQL.
[src:immudb/database-p01] On the programming side, libraries known as object–relational mappings (ORMs) attempt to solve the same problem.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Database sales grew rapidly during the dotcom bubble and, after its end, the rise of ecommerce.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The popularity of open source databases such as MySQL has grown since 2000, to the extent that Ken Jacobs of Oracle said in 2005 that perhaps "these guys are doing to us what we did to IBM".
[src:immudb/database-p01] XML databases are a type of structured document-oriented database that allows querying based on XML document attributes.
[src:immudb/database-p01] XML databases are mostly used in applications where the data is conveniently viewed as a collection of documents, with a structure that can vary from the very flexible to the highly rigid: examples include scientific articles, patents, tax filings, and personnel records.
[src:immudb/database-p01] NoSQL databases are often very fast, do not require fixed table schemas, avoid join operations by storing denormalized data, and are designed to scale horizontally.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Some NoSQL databases, including graph databases such as Neo4j, represent data as nodes and edges to model relationships between entities.
[src:immudb/database-p01] In recent years, there has been a strong demand for massively distributed databases with high partition tolerance, but according to the CAP theorem, it is impossible for a distributed system to simultaneously provide consistency, availability, and partition tolerance guarantees.
[src:immudb/database-p01] A distributed system can satisfy any two of these guarantees at the same time, but not all three.
[src:immudb/database-p01] For that reason, many NoSQL databases are using what is called eventual consistency to provide both availability and partition tolerance guarantees with a reduced level of data consistency.
[src:immudb/database-p01] NewSQL is a class of modern relational databases that aims to provide the same scalable performance of NoSQL systems for online transaction processing (read-write) workloads while still using SQL and maintaining the ACID guarantees of a traditional database system.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Databases are used to support internal operations of organizations and to underpin online interactions with customers and suppliers (see Enterprise software).
[src:immudb/database-p01] Databases are used to hold administrative information and more specialized data, such as engineering data or economic models.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Examples include computerized library systems, flight reservation systems, computerized parts inventory systems, and many content management systems that store websites as collections of webpages in a database.
[src:immudb/database-p01] One way to classify databases involves the type of their contents, for example: bibliographic, document-text, statistical, or multimedia objects.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Another way is by their application area, for example: accounting, music compositions, movies, banking, manufacturing, or insurance.
[src:immudb/database-p01] A third way is by some technical aspect, such as the database structure or interface type.
[src:immudb/database-p01] This section lists a few of the adjectives used to characterize different kinds of databases.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Connolly and Begg define database management system (DBMS) as a "software system that enables users to define, create, maintain and control access to the database." Examples of DBMS's include MySQL, MariaDB, PostgreSQL, Microsoft SQL Server, Oracle Database, and Microsoft Access.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The DBMS acronym is sometimes extended to indicate the underlying database model, with RDBMS for the relational, OODBMS for the object (oriented) and ORDBMS for the object–relational model.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Other extensions can indicate some other characteristics, such as DDBMS for a distributed database management systems.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The functionality provided by a DBMS can vary enormously.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The core functionality is the storage, retrieval and update of data.
[src:immudb/database-p01] It is also generally to be expected the DBMS will provide a set of utilities for such purposes as may be necessary to administer the database effectively, including import, export, monitoring, defragmentation and analysis utilities.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The core part of the DBMS interacting between the database and the application interface sometimes referred to as the database engine.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Often DBMSs will have configuration parameters that can be statically and dynamically tuned, for example the maximum amount of main memory on a server the database can use.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The trend is to minimize the amount of manual configuration, and for cases such as embedded databases the need to target zero-administration is paramount.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The large major enterprise DBMSs have tended to increase in size and functionality and have involved up to thousands of human years of development effort throughout their lifetime.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Early multi-user DBMS typically only allowed for the application to reside on the same computer with access via terminals or terminal emulation software.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The client–server architecture was a development where the application resided on a client desktop and the database on a server allowing the processing to be distributed.
[src:immudb/database-p01] This evolved into a multitier architecture incorporating application servers and web servers with the end user interface via a web browser with the database only directly connected to the adjacent tier.
[src:immudb/database-p01] A general-purpose DBMS will provide public application programming interfaces (API) and optionally a processor for database languages such as SQL to allow applications to be written to interact with and manipulate the database.
[src:immudb/database-p01] A special purpose DBMS may use a private API and be specifically customized and linked to a single application.
[src:immudb/database-p01] For example, an email system performs many of the functions of a general-purpose DBMS such as message insertion, message deletion, attachment handling, blocklist lookup, associating messages an email address and so forth however these functions are limited to what is required to handle email.
[src:immudb/database-p01] External interaction with the database will be via an application program that interfaces with the DBMS.
[src:immudb/database-p01] This can range from a database tool that allows users to execute SQL queries textually or graphically, to a website that happens to use a database to store and search information.
[src:immudb/database-p01] A programmer will code interactions to the database (sometimes referred to as a datasource) via an application program interface (API) or via a database language.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The particular API or language chosen will need to be supported by DBMS, possibly indirectly via a preprocessor or a bridging API.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Some API's aim to be database independent, ODBC being a commonly known example.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Other common API's include JDBC and ADO.NET.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Database languages are specific to a particular data model.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Database storage is the container of the physical materialization of a database.
[src:immudb/database-p01] It comprises the *internal* (physical) *level* in the database architecture.
[src:immudb/database-p01] It also contains all the information needed (e.g., metadata, "data about the data", and internal data structures) to reconstruct the *conceptual level* and *external level* from the internal level when needed.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Databases as digital objects contain three layers of information which must be stored: the data, the structure, and the semantics.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Proper storage of all three layers is needed for future preservation and longevity of the database.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Putting data into permanent storage is generally the responsibility of the database engine a.k.a.
[src:immudb/database-p01] A DBMS, while in operation, always has its database residing in several types of storage (e.g., memory and external storage).
[src:immudb/database-p01] The database data and the additional needed information, possibly in very large amounts, are coded into bits.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Some DBMSs support specifying which character encoding was used to store data, so multiple encodings can be used in the same database.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Various low-level database storage structures are used by the storage engine to serialize the data model so it can be written to the medium of choice.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Techniques such as indexing may be used to improve performance.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Conventional storage is row-oriented, but there are also column-oriented and correlation databases.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Often storage redundancy is employed to increase performance.
[src:immudb/database-p01] A common example is storing *materialized views*, which consist of frequently needed *external views* or query results.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Storing such views saves the expensive computing them each time they are needed.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The downsides of materialized views are the overhead incurred when updating them to keep them synchronized with their original updated database data, and the cost of storage redundancy.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Updates of a replicated object need to be synchronized across the object copies.
[src:immudb/database-p01] In many cases, the entire database is replicated.
[src:immudb/database-p01] With data virtualization, the data used remains in its original locations and real-time access is established to allow analytics across multiple sources.
[src:immudb/database-p01] This can aid in resolving some technical difficulties such as compatibility problems when combining data from various platforms, lowering the risk of error caused by faulty data, and guaranteeing that the newest data is used.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Furthermore, avoiding the creation of a new database containing personal information can make it easier to comply with privacy regulations.
[src:immudb/database-p01] However, with data virtualization, the connection to all necessary data sources must be operational as there is no local copy of the data, which is one of the main drawbacks of the approach.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Database security deals with all various aspects of protecting the database content, its owners, and its users.
[src:immudb/database-p01] It ranges from protection from intentional unauthorized database uses to unintentional database accesses by unauthorized entities (e.g., a person or a computer program).
[src:immudb/database-p01] Database access control deals with controlling who (a person or a certain computer program) are allowed to access what information in the database.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Database access controls are set by special authorized (by the database owner) personnel that uses dedicated protected security DBMS interfaces.
[src:immudb/database-p01] This may be managed directly on an individual basis, or by the assignment of individuals and privileges to groups, or (in the most elaborate models) through the assignment of individuals and groups to roles which are then granted entitlements.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Data security prevents unauthorized users from viewing or updating the database.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Using passwords, users are allowed access to the entire database or subsets of it called "subschemas".
[src:immudb/database-p01] For example, an employee database can contain all the data about an individual employee, but one group of users may be authorized to view only payroll data, while others are allowed access to only work history and medical data.
[src:immudb/database-p01] If the DBMS provides a way to interactively enter and update the database, as well as interrogate it, this capability allows for managing personal databases.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Change and access logging records who accessed which attributes, what was changed, and when it was changed.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Logging services allow for a forensic database audit later by keeping a record of access occurrences and changes.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Sometimes application-level code is used to record changes rather than leaving this in the database.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Monitoring can be set up to attempt to detect security breaches.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Therefore, organizations must take database security seriously because of the many benefits it provides.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Organizations will be safeguarded from security breaches and hacking activities like firewall intrusion, virus spread, and ransom ware.
[src:immudb/database-p01] This helps in protecting the company's essential information, which cannot be shared with outsiders at any cause.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Database transactions can be used to introduce some level of fault tolerance and data integrity after recovery from a crash.
[src:immudb/database-p01] A database transaction is a unit of work, typically encapsulating a number of operations over a database (e.g., reading a database object, writing, acquiring or releasing a lock, etc.), an abstraction supported in database and also other systems.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Each transaction has well defined boundaries in terms of which program/code executions are included in that transaction (determined by the transaction's programmer via special transaction commands).
[src:immudb/database-p01] The acronym ACID describes some ideal properties of a database transaction: atomicity, consistency, isolation, and durability.
[src:immudb/database-p01] A database built with one DBMS is not portable to another DBMS (i.e., the other DBMS cannot run it).
[src:immudb/database-p01] However, in some situations, it is desirable to migrate a database from one DBMS to another.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The reasons are primarily economical (different DBMSs may have different total costs of ownership or TCOs), functional, and operational (different DBMSs may have different capabilities).
[src:immudb/database-p01] The migration involves the database's transformation from one DBMS type to another.
[src:immudb/database-p01] The transformation should maintain (if possible) the database related application (i.e., all related application programs) intact.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Thus, the database's conceptual and external architectural levels should be maintained in the transformation.
[src:immudb/database-p01] It may be desired that also some aspects of the architecture internal level are maintained.
[src:immudb/database-p01] A complex or large database migration may be a complicated and costly (one-time) project by itself, which should be factored into the decision to migrate.
[src:immudb/database-p01] This is in spite of the fact that tools may exist to help migration between specific DBMSs.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Typically, a DBMS vendor provides tools to help import databases from other popular DBMSs.
[src:immudb/database-p01] After designing a database for an application, the next stage is building the database.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Typically, an appropriate general-purpose DBMS can be selected to be used for this purpose.
[src:immudb/database-p01] A DBMS provides the needed user interfaces to be used by database administrators to define the needed application's data structures within the DBMS's respective data model.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Other user interfaces are used to select needed DBMS parameters (like security related, storage allocation parameters, etc.).
[src:immudb/database-p01] In some cases, the database becomes operational while empty of application data, and data are accumulated during its operation.
[src:immudb/database-p01] After the database is created, initialized and populated it needs to be maintained.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Various database parameters may need changing and the database may need to be tuned (tuning) for better performance; application's data structures may be changed or added, new related application programs may be written to add to the application's functionality, etc.
[src:immudb/database-p01] Sometimes it is desired to bring a database back to a previous state (for many reasons, e.g., cases when the database is found corrupted due to a software error, or if it has been updated with erroneous data).
[src:immudb/database-p01] To achieve this, a backup operation is done occasionally or continuously, where each desired database state (i.e., the values of its data and their embedding in database's data structures) is kept within dedicated backup files (many techniques exist to do this effectively).
[src:immudb/database-p01] When it is decided by a database administrator to bring the database back to this state (e.g., by specifying this state by a desired point in time when the database was in this state), these files are used to restore that state.
[src:immudb/database-p02] Static analysis techniques for software verification can be applied also in the scenario of query languages.
[src:immudb/database-p02] In particular, the *Abstract interpretation framework has been extended to the field of query languages for relational databases as a way to support sound approximation techniques.
[src:immudb/database-p02] The semantics of query languages can be tuned according to suitable abstractions of the concrete domain of data.
[src:immudb/database-p02] The abstraction of relational database systems has many interesting applications, in particular, for security purposes, such as fine-grained access control, watermarking, etc.
[src:immudb/database-p02] Increasingly, there are calls for a single system that incorporates all of these core functionalities into the same build, test, and deployment framework for database management and source control.
[src:immudb/database-p02] Borrowing from other developments in the software industry, some market such offerings as "DevOps for database".
[src:immudb/database-p02] The first task of a database designer is to produce a conceptual data model that reflects the structure of the information to be held in the database.
[src:immudb/database-p02] A common approach to this is to develop an entity–relationship model, often with the aid of drawing tools.
[src:immudb/database-p02] Another popular approach is the Unified Modeling Language.
[src:immudb/database-p02] A successful data model will accurately reflect the possible state of the external world being modeled: for example, if people can have more than one phone number, it will allow this information to be captured.
[src:immudb/database-p02] The answers to these questions establish definitions of the terminology used for entities (customers, products, flights, flight segments) and their relationships and attributes.
[src:immudb/database-p02] Producing the conceptual data model sometimes involves input from business processes, or the analysis of workflow in the organization.
[src:immudb/database-p02] This can help to establish what information is needed in the database, and what can be left out.
[src:immudb/database-p02] For example, it can help when deciding whether the database needs to hold historic data as well as current data.
[src:immudb/database-p02] Having produced a conceptual data model that users are happy with, the next stage is to translate this into a schema that implements the relevant data structures within the database.
[src:immudb/database-p02] This process is often called logical database design, and the output is a logical data model expressed in the form of a schema.
[src:immudb/database-p02] Whereas the conceptual data model is (in theory at least) independent of the choice of database technology, the logical data model will be expressed in terms of a particular database model supported by the chosen DBMS.
[src:immudb/database-p02] (The terms *data model* and *database model* are often used interchangeably, but in this article we use *data model* for the design of a specific database, and *database model* for the modeling notation used to express that design).
[src:immudb/database-p02] The most popular database model for general-purpose databases is the relational model, or more precisely, the relational model as represented by the SQL language.
[src:immudb/database-p02] The process of creating a logical database design using this model uses a methodical approach known as normalization.
[src:immudb/database-p02] The goal of normalization is to ensure that each elementary "fact" is only recorded in one place, so that insertions, updates, and deletions automatically maintain consistency.
[src:immudb/database-p02] The final stage of database design is to make the decisions that affect performance, scalability, recovery, security, and the like, which depend on the particular DBMS.
[src:immudb/database-p02] This is often called *physical database design*, and the output is the physical data model.
[src:immudb/database-p02] A key goal during this stage is data independence, meaning that the decisions made for performance optimization purposes should be invisible to end-users and applications.
[src:immudb/database-p02] There are two types of data independence: Physical data independence and logical data independence.
[src:immudb/database-p02] Physical design is driven mainly by performance requirements, and requires a good knowledge of the expected workload and access patterns, and a deep understanding of the features offered by the chosen DBMS.
[src:immudb/database-p02] Another aspect of physical database design is security.
[src:immudb/database-p02] It involves both defining access control to database objects as well as defining security levels and methods for the data itself.
[src:immudb/database-p02] A database model is a type of data model that determines the logical structure of a database and fundamentally determines in which manner data can be stored, organized, and manipulated.
[src:immudb/database-p02] The most popular example of a database model is the relational model (or the SQL approximation of relational), which uses a table-based format.
[src:immudb/database-p02] An object–relational database combines the two related structures.
[src:immudb/database-p02] While there is typically only one conceptual and internal view of the data, there can be any number of different external views.
[src:immudb/database-p02] This allows users to see database information in a more business-related way rather than from a technical, processing viewpoint.
[src:immudb/database-p02] For example, a financial department of a company needs the payment details of all employees as part of the company's expenses, but does not need details about employees that are in the interest of the human resources department.
[src:immudb/database-p02] Thus different departments need different *views* of the company's database.
[src:immudb/database-p02] The three-level database architecture relates to the concept of *data independence* which was one of the major initial driving forces of the relational model.
[src:immudb/database-p02] The idea is that changes made at a certain level do not affect the view at a higher level.
[src:immudb/database-p02] For example, changes in the internal level do not affect application programs written using conceptual level interfaces, which reduces the impact of making physical changes to improve performance.
[src:immudb/database-p02] The conceptual view provides a level of indirection between internal and external.
[src:immudb/database-p02] On the one hand it provides a common view of the database, independent of different external view structures, and on the other hand it abstracts away details of how the data are stored or managed (internal level).
[src:immudb/database-p02] In principle every level, and even every external view, can be presented by a different data model.
[src:immudb/database-p02] In practice usually a given DBMS uses the same data model for both the external and the conceptual levels (e.g., relational model).
[src:immudb/database-p02] The internal level, which is hidden inside the DBMS and depends on its implementation, requires a different level of detail and uses its own types of data structure types.
[src:immudb/database-p02] Database technology has been an active research topic since the 1960s, both in academia and in the research and development groups of companies (for example IBM Research).
[src:immudb/database-p02] Research activity includes theory and development of prototypes.
[src:immudb/database-p02] Notable research topics have included models, the atomic transaction concept, related concurrency control techniques, query languages and query optimization methods, RAID, and more.
[src:immudb/database-p02] The database research area has several dedicated academic journals (for example, *ACM Transactions on Database Systems*-TODS, *Data and Knowledge Engineering*-DKE) and annual conferences (e.g., ACM SIGMOD, ACM PODS, VLDB, IEEE ICDE).
[src:immudb/immutable-object] In object-oriented (OO) and functional programming, an **immutable object** (unchangeable object) is an object whose state cannot be modified after it is created.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] This is in contrast to a **mutable object** (changeable object), which can be modified after it is created.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] In some cases, an object is considered immutable even if some internally used attributes change, but the object's state appears unchanging from an external point of view.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] For example, an object that uses memoization to cache the results of expensive computations could still be considered an immutable object.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Strings and other concrete objects are typically expressed as immutable objects to improve readability and runtime efficiency in object-oriented programming.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Immutable objects are also useful because they are inherently thread-safe.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Other benefits are that they are simpler to understand and reason about and offer higher security than mutable objects.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] In imperative programming, values held in program variables whose content never changes are known as *constants* to differentiate them from variables that could be altered during execution.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Examples include conversion factors from meters to feet, or the value of pi to several decimal places.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Read-only fields may be calculated when the program runs (unlike constants, which are known beforehand), but never change after they are initialized.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Sometimes, one talks of certain *fields* of an object being immutable.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] This means that there is no way to change those parts of the object state, even though other parts of the object may be changeable (*weakly immutable*).
[src:immudb/immutable-object] If all fields are immutable, then the object is immutable.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] If the whole object cannot be extended by another class, the object is called *strongly immutable*.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] This might, for example, help to explicitly enforce certain invariants about certain data in the object staying the same through the lifetime of the object.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] In some languages, this is done with a keyword (e.g.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] `const` in C++, `final` in Java) that designates the field as immutable.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Some languages reverse it: in OCaml, fields of an object or record are by default immutable, and must be explicitly marked with `mutable` to be so.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] In most object-oriented languages, objects can be referred to using references.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Some examples of such languages are Java, C++, C#, VB.NET, and many scripting languages, such as Perl, Python, and Ruby.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] In this case, it matters whether the state of an object can vary when objects are shared via references.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] If an object is known to be immutable, it is preferred to create a reference of it instead of copying the entire object.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] This is done to conserve memory by preventing data duplication and avoid calls to constructors and destructors; it also results in a potential boost in execution speed.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] The reference copying technique is much more difficult to use for mutable objects, because if any user of a mutable object reference changes it, all other users of that reference see the change.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] If this is not the intended effect, it can be difficult to notify the other users to have them respond correctly.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] In these situations, defensive copying of the entire object rather than the reference is usually an easy but costly solution.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] The observer pattern is an alternative technique for handling changes to mutable objects.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] A technique that blends the advantages of **mutable** and **immutable** objects, and is supported directly in almost all modern hardware, is copy-on-write (COW).
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Using this technique, when a user asks the system to copy an object, it instead merely creates a new reference that still points to the same object.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] As soon as a user attempts to modify the object through a particular reference, the system makes a real copy, applies the modification to that, and sets the reference to refer to the new copy.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] The other users are unaffected, because they still refer to the original object.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Therefore, under COW, all users appear to have a mutable version of their objects, although in the case that users do not modify their objects, the space-saving and speed advantages of immutable objects are preserved.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Copy-on-write is popular in virtual memory systems because it allows them to save memory space while still correctly handling anything an application program might do.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] The practice of always using references in place of copies of equal objects is known as *interning*.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] If interning is used, two objects are considered equal if and only if their references, typically represented as pointers or integers, are equal.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Some languages do this automatically: for example, Python automatically interns short strings.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] If the algorithm that implements interning is guaranteed to do so in every case that it is possible, then comparing objects for equality is reduced to comparing their pointers – a substantial gain in speed in most applications.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] (Even if the algorithm is not guaranteed to be comprehensive, there still exists the possibility of a fast path case improvement when the objects are equal and use the same reference.) Interning is generally only useful for immutable objects.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Immutable objects can be useful in multi-threaded applications.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Multiple threads can act on data represented by immutable objects without concern of the data being changed by other threads.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Immutable objects are therefore considered more *thread-safe* than mutable objects.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Immutability does not imply that the object as stored in the computer's memory is unwriteable.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Rather, immutability is a compile-time construct that indicates what a programmer can do through the normal interface of the object, not necessarily what they can absolutely do (for instance, by circumventing the type system or violating const correctness in C or C++).
[src:immudb/immutable-object] In Python, Java and the .NET Framework, strings are immutable objects.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Both Java and the .NET Framework have mutable versions of string.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] In Java these are `StringBuffer` and `StringBuilder` (mutable versions of Java `String`) and in .NET this is `StringBuilder` (mutable version of .Net `String`).
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Python 3 has a mutable string (bytes) variant, named `bytearray`.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Additionally, all of the primitive wrapper classes in Java are immutable.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Similar patterns are the Immutable Interface and Immutable Wrapper.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] In pure functional programming languages it is not possible to create mutable objects without extending the language (e.g. via a mutable references library or a foreign function interface), so all objects are immutable.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] In Ada, any object is declared either *variable* (i.e. mutable; typically the implicit default), or `constant` (i.e. immutable) via the `constant` keyword.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Subprogram parameters are immutable in the *in* mode, and mutable in the *in out* and *out* modes.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] In C# one can enforce immutability of the fields of a class with the `readonly` statement.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] By enforcing all the fields as immutable, the type becomes an immutable type.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] In C++, a const-correct implementation of `ShoppingCart` would allow the user to create instances of the class and then use them as either `const` (immutable) or mutable, as desired, by providing two different versions of the `items()` method.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Note that, when there is a data member that is a pointer or reference to another object, then it is possible to mutate the object pointed to or referenced only within a non-const method.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] C++ also provides abstract (as opposed to bitwise) immutability via the `mutable` keyword, which lets a member variable be changed from within a `const` method.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] In D, there exist two type qualifiers, `const` and `immutable`, for variables that cannot be changed.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Unlike C++'s `const`, Java's `final`, and C#'s `readonly`, they are transitive and recursively apply to anything reachable through references of such a variable.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] The difference between `const` and `immutable` is what they apply to: `const` is a property of the variable: there might legally exist mutable references to referred value, i.e. the value can actually change.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] In contrast, `immutable` is a property of the referred value: the value and anything transitively reachable from it cannot change (without breaking the type system, leading to undefined behavior).
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Any reference of that value must be marked `const` or `immutable`.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Basically for any unqualified type `T`, `const(T)` is the disjoint union of `T` (mutable) and `immutable(T)`.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] For a mutable `Example` object, its `mutableField` can be written to.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] For a `const(Example)` object, `mutableField` cannot be modified, it inherits `const`; `immutableField` is still immutable as it is the stronger guarantee.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] For an `immutable(Example)`, all fields are immutable.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Inside the braces, `c` might refer to the same object as `m`, so mutations to `m` could indirectly change `c` as well.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Also, `c` might refer to the same object as `i`, but since the value then is immutable, there are no changes.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] However, `m` and `i` cannot legally refer to the same object.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] In the language of guarantees, mutable has no guarantees (the function might change the object), `const` is an outward-only guarantee that the function will not change anything, and `immutable` is a bidirectional guarantee (the function will not change the value and the caller must not change it).
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Values that are `const` or `immutable` must be initialized by direct assignment at the point of declaration or by a constructor.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Because `const` parameters forget if the value was mutable or not, a similar construct, `inout`, acts, in a sense, as a variable for mutability information.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] A function of type `const(S) function(const(T))` returns `const(S)` typed values for mutable, const and immutable arguments.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] In contrast, a function of type `inout(S) function(inout(T))` returns `S` for mutable `T` arguments, `const(S)` for `const(T)` values, and `immutable(S)` for `immutable(T)` values.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Casting immutable values to mutable inflicts undefined behavior upon change, even if the original value comes from a mutable origin.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Casting mutable values to immutable can be legal when there remain no mutable references afterward.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] The type `string` is an alias for `immutable(char)[]`, i.e. a typed slice of memory of immutable characters.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Making substrings is cheap, as it just copies and modifies a pointer and a length filed, and safe, as the underlying data cannot be changed.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Objects of type `const(char)[]` can refer to strings, but also to mutable buffers.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Making a shallow copy of a const or immutable value removes the outer layer of immutability: Copying an immutable string (`immutable(char[])`) returns a string (`immutable(char)[]`).
[src:immudb/immutable-object] The immutable pointer and length are being copied and the copies are mutable.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] The referred data has not been copied and keeps its qualifier, in the example `immutable`.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] It can be stripped by making a depper copy, e.g. using the `dup` function.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] The method `toLowerCase()` does not change the data "ABC" that `s` contains.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Instead, a new String object is instantiated and given the data "abc" during its construction.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] A reference to this String object is returned by the `toLowerCase()` method.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Now the String `s` references a new String object that contains "abc".
[src:immudb/immutable-object] There is nothing in the syntax of the *declaration* of the class String that enforces it as immutable; rather, none of the String class's methods ever affect the data that a String object contains, thus making it immutable.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] The keyword `final` (detailed article) is used in implementing immutable primitive types and object references, but it cannot, by itself, make *the objects themselves* immutable.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Primitive type variables (`int`, `long`, `short`, etc.) can be reassigned after being defined.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Reference types cannot be made immutable just by using the `final` keyword.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Primitive wrappers (`Integer`, `Long`, `Short`, `Double`, `Float`, `Character`, `Byte`, `Boolean`) are also all immutable.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Immutable classes can be implemented by following a few simple guidelines.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] In JavaScript, all primitive types (Undefined, Null, Boolean, Number, BigInt, String, Symbol) are immutable, but custom objects are generally mutable.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] To simulate immutability in an object, one may define properties as read-only (writable: false).
[src:immudb/immutable-object] However, the approach above still lets new properties be added.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Alternatively, one may use Object.freeze to make existing objects immutable.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] With the implementation of ECMA262, JavaScript has the ability to create immutable references that cannot be reassigned.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] However, using a `const` declaration doesn't mean that value of the read-only reference is immutable, just that the name cannot be assigned to a new value.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] The use of immutable state has become a rising trend in JavaScript since the introduction of React, which favours Flux-like state management patterns such as Redux.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] In PHP have readonly properties since version 8.1 and readonly classes since version 8.2.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] In Python, some built-in types (numbers, Booleans, strings, tuples, frozensets) are immutable, but custom classes are generally mutable.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] The standard library helpers `collections.namedtuple` and `typing.NamedTuple`, available from Python 3.6 onward, create simple immutable classes.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Introduced in Python 3.7, `dataclasses` allow developers to emulate immutability with frozen instances.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] If a frozen dataclass is built, `dataclasses` will override `__setattr__()` and `__delattr__()` to raise `FrozenInstanceError` if invoked.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Racket substantially diverges from other Scheme implementations by making its core pair type ("cons cells") immutable.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Instead, it provides a parallel mutable pair type, via `mcons`, `mcar`, `set-mcar!` etc.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] In addition, many immutable types are supported, for example, immutable strings and vectors, and these are used extensively.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] The language also supports immutable hash tables, implemented functionally, and immutable dictionaries.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Rust's ownership system allows developers to declare immutable variables, and pass immutable references.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] By default, all variables and references are immutable.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Mutable variables and references are explicitly created with the `mut` keyword.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Constant items in Rust are always immutable.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] In Scala, any entity (narrowly, a binding) can be defined as mutable or immutable: in the declaration, one can use `val` (value) for immutable entities and `var` (variable) for mutable ones.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] Note that even though an immutable binding can not be reassigned, it may still refer to a mutable object and it is still possible to call mutating methods on that object: the *binding* is immutable, but the underlying *object* may be mutable.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] defines an immutable entity `maxValue` (the integer type is inferred at compile-time) and a mutable entity named `currentValue`.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] By default, collection classes such as `List` and `Map` are immutable, so update-methods return a new instance rather than mutating an existing one.
[src:immudb/immutable-object] While this may sound inefficient, the implementation of these classes and their guarantees of immutability mean that the new instance can re-use existing nodes, which, especially in the case of creating copies, is very efficient.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] A hash tree allows efficient and secure verification of the contents of a large data structure.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] A hash tree is a generalization of a hash list and a hash chain.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] Demonstrating that a leaf node is a part of a given binary hash tree requires computing a number of hashes proportional to the logarithm of the number of leaf nodes in the tree.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] Conversely, in a hash list, the number is proportional to the number of leaf nodes itself.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] A Merkle tree is therefore an efficient example of a cryptographic commitment scheme, in which the root of the tree is seen as a commitment and leaf nodes may be revealed and proven to be part of the original commitment.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] The concept of a hash tree is named after Ralph Merkle, who patented it in 1979.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] Hash trees can be used to verify any kind of data stored, handled and transferred in and between computers.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] They can help ensure that data blocks received from other peers in a peer-to-peer network are received undamaged and unaltered, and even to check that the other peers do not lie and send fake blocks.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] Suggestions have been made to use hash trees in trusted computing systems.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] A hash tree is a tree of hashes in which the leaves (i.e., leaf nodes, sometimes also called "leafs") are hashes of data blocks in, for instance, a file or set of files.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] Nodes farther up in the tree are the hashes of their respective children.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] For example, in the above picture *hash 0* is the result of hashing the concatenation of *hash 0-0* and *hash 0-1*.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] That is, *hash 0* = *hash*( *hash 0-0* + *hash 0-1* ) where "+" denotes concatenation.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] Most hash tree implementations are binary (two child nodes under each node) but they can just as well use many more child nodes under each node.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] Usually, a cryptographic hash function such as SHA-2 is used for the hashing.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] If the hash tree only needs to protect against unintentional damage, non-cryptographic checksums such as CRCs can be used.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] In the top of a hash tree there is a *top hash* (or *root hash* or *master hash*).
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] Before downloading a file on a P2P network, in most cases the top hash is acquired from a trusted source, for instance a friend or a web site that is known to have good recommendations of files to download.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] When the top hash is available, the hash tree can be received from any non-trusted source, like any peer in the P2P network.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] Then, the received hash tree is checked against the trusted top hash, and if the hash tree is damaged or fake, another hash tree from another source will be tried until the program finds one that matches the top hash.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] The main difference from a hash list is that one branch of the hash tree can be downloaded at a time and the integrity of each branch can be checked immediately, even though the whole tree is not available yet.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] For example, in the picture, the integrity of *data block L2* can be verified immediately if the tree already contains *hash 0-0* and *hash 1* by hashing the data block and iteratively combining the result with *hash 0-0* and then *hash 1* and finally comparing the result with the *top hash*.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] Similarly, the integrity of *data block L3* can be verified if the tree already has *hash 1-1* and *hash 0*.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] This can be an advantage since it is efficient to split files up in very small data blocks so that only small blocks have to be re-downloaded if they get damaged.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] If the hashed file is big, such a hash list or hash chain becomes fairly big.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] But if it is a tree, one small branch can be downloaded quickly, the integrity of the branch can be checked, and then the downloading of data blocks can start.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] The Merkle hash root does not indicate the tree depth, enabling a second-preimage attack in which an attacker creates a document other than the original that has the same Merkle hash root.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] For the example above, an attacker can create a new document containing two data blocks, where the first is *hash 0-0* + *hash 0-1*, and the second is *hash 1-0* + *hash 1-1*.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] One simple fix is defined in Certificate Transparency: when computing leaf node hashes, a 0x00 byte is prepended to the hash data, while 0x01 is prepended when computing internal node hashes.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] Limiting the hash tree size is a prerequisite of some formal security proofs, and helps in making some proofs tighter.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] Some implementations limit the tree depth using hash tree depth prefixes before hashes, so any extracted hash chain is defined to be valid only if the prefix decreases at each step and is still positive when the leaf is reached.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] The Tiger tree hash is a widely used form of hash tree.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] It uses a binary hash tree (two child nodes under each node), usually has a data block size of 1024 bytes and uses the Tiger hash.
[src:immudb/merkle-tree] Tiger tree hashes are used in Gnutella, Gnutella2, and Direct Connect P2P file sharing protocols and in file sharing applications such as Phex, BearShare, LimeWire, Shareaza, DC++ and gtk-gnutella.
[src:immudb/reading] Most of the methods in SDKs have `Verified` equivalent, i.e.
[src:immudb/reading] The only difference is that with `Verified` methods proofs needed to mathematically verify that the data was not tampered are returned by the server and the verification is done automatically by SDKs.
[src:immudb/reading] Note that generating that proof has a slight performance impact, so primitives are allowed without the proof.
[src:immudb/reading] It is still possible to get the proofs for a specific item at any time, so the decision about when or how frequently to do checks (with the Verify version of a method) is completely up to the user.
[src:immudb/reading] It's possible also to use dedicated auditors to ensure the database consistency, but the pattern in which every client is also an auditor is the more interesting one.
[src:immudb/reading] `Get`/`VerifiedGet` and `Set`/`VerifiedSet` methods allow for basic operations on a Key Value level.
[src:immudb/reading] In addition, `GetAll` and `SetAll` methods allow for adding and reading in a single transaction.
[src:immudb/reading] See transactions chapter for more details.
[src:immudb/reading] Note that `value` is a primitive byte array.
[src:immudb/reading] Also, `set` method is overloaded to allow receiving the `key` parameter as a `byte[]` data type.
[src:immudb/reading] You can retrieve a key on a specific transaction with `GetAt`/`VerifiedGetAt`.
[src:immudb/reading] If you need to check the last value of a key after given transaction (which represent state of the indexer), you can use `GetSince`/`VerifiedGetSince`.
[src:immudb/reading] Each historical value for a single key is attached a revision number.
[src:immudb/reading] Revision numbers start with 1 and each overwrite of the same key results in a new sequential revision number assignment.
[src:immudb/reading] A negative revision number can also be specified which means the nth historical value, e.g. -1 is the previous value, -2 is the one before and so on.
