[src:immudb/reading] ::: tab Node.js This feature is not yet supported or not documented.
[src:immudb/reading] It's possible to retrieve all the keys inside a specific transaction.
[src:immudb/reading] immudb can check additional preconditions before the write operation is made.
[src:immudb/reading] Precondition is checked atomically with the write operation.
[src:immudb/reading] It can be then used to ensure consistent state of data inside the database.
[src:immudb/reading] In many cases, keys used for constraints will be the same as keys for written entries.
[src:immudb/reading] A good example here is a situation when a value is set only if that key does not exist.
[src:immudb/reading] This is not strictly required - keys used in constraints do not have to be the same or even overlap with keys for modified entries.
[src:immudb/reading] An example would be if only one of two keys should exist in the database.
[src:immudb/reading] In such case, the first key will be modified and the second key will be used for MustNotExist constraint.
[src:immudb/reading] A write operation using precondition can not be done in an asynchronous way.
[src:immudb/reading] Preconditions are checked twice when processing such requests - first check is done against the current state of internal index, the second check is done just before persisting the write and requires up-to-date index.
[src:immudb/reading] Preconditions are available on `SetAll`, `Reference` and `ExecAll` operations.
[src:immudb/reading] In go sdk, the `schema` package contains convenient wrappers for creating constraint objects, such as `schema.PreconditionKeyMustNotExist`.
[src:immudb/reading] ::: tab Java This feature is not yet supported or not documented.
